## Answer from author with ChatGPT
### **Title**
Early Experience in Nagoya City Waterworks Bureau and the Evolution of End-User Computing in Japan (1980‚Äì)
### **Abstract**
In the early 1980s, while working at the Nagoya City Waterworks Bureau, an analytical model for water rate structures was constructed using 8-bit computers and programmable calculators. At that time, computational processing within administrative agencies relied on manual labor or large-scale general-purpose computers. This research represents an early Japanese case of **End-User Computing (EUC)**, where field personnel (End Users) programmed themselves to contribute to decision-making and policy improvement.
This analysis clearly visualized the issues with the existing fee structure and proposed improvements closely resembling the current water rate system. This achievement was recognized at academic conferences, notably for its focus on **computational modeling linked to practical application and social value** rather than purely theoretical research.
Building on this experience, recent research and activities have expanded into open-source development, control systems, embedded operating systems (OSEK), communication protocols, digital government, and Agile methodologies.
### **Keywords**
End-User Computing, Public Utility Informatics, Government IT, Embedded Systems, OSEK OS, Rate Modeling, Digital Transformation, Smart City, Water Tariff Structure, Early Computing
## **üìå 2. Qiita Article Draft (friendly, technical style)**
Perfect for your Qiita audience who likes engineering stories.
### **Title Idea**
> **My Story of Starting Programming in the 1980s Government Sector ‚Äî End-User Computing Began with 8-bit Machines and Water Tariff Analysis**
### **Body **
At age 21, I began working at the Nagoya City Waterworks and Sewerage Bureau.
Back then, there was no internet or smartphones; we used 8-bit computers and programmable calculators.
I had studied economics in university. Papers on abstract theory didn't win prizes or recognition.
While working in field sales, customers pointed out unfairness and irrationality in water tariffs.
I used computers to build a numerical model of the tariff structure and ran simulations.
‚ÄúIs the structure of water rates truly rational?‚Äù
A Transportation Bureau employee submitted the same verification paper under the title ‚ÄúFree Buses‚Äù and won first place; my paper took second.
The fact that employees from public utility companies won awards for papers on pricing became a topic of discussion at the time.
* Demand curve
* Cost structure
* Supply capacity
* Pricing policy for public infrastructure
* Rate tiers
We calculated estimates for these factors, presented issues and improvement proposals, and the research was recognized with an award.
As a result, the pricing structure at the time was reviewed and improved to the current structure.
Looking back now, I believe this was a pioneering example of **End-User Computing (programming as problem-solving by field users)**.
